                {"src": "ellicott", "attr": "Ellicott's Commentary", "html": "<p>The appeal is not only to their past experience when first they listened to Paul's preaching, but also to their present experience of facts going on among them. The first great outpouring of the Spirit, both in its miraculous and non-miraculous forms, though checked, had not entirely ceased; and the Galatians might see that the channel which was still operative was faith, not law.</p>"},
                {"src": "clarke", "attr": "Adam Clarke", "html": "<p>He therefore that ministereth to you the Spirit — the apostle means himself. He had been the means of conveying the Holy Spirit to them, and by that Spirit he wrought miracles among them. The word <em>epichoregon</em>, which we translate ministereth, is very emphatic — it signifies leading up the chorus, bringing up one after another, adding grace to grace in a continuous, abundant supply.</p>"},
