                {"src": "ellicott", "attr": "Ellicott's Commentary", "html": "<p>The main point of the Apostle's argument is the superiority of faith over the Law. He has, however, also in view the ulterior consequences of that superiority. Unlike the Law, faith is open to all — Gentiles as well as Jews. The promise, therefore, being annexed to faith, contained the death-blow of all those exclusive privileges which the Judaising party in Galatia claimed for themselves.</p>"},
